  "strings" : {
    "" : {

    },
    "\nIf an Alif Mad is followed by a letter with a shaddah, the elongation extends to 6 counts." : {

    },
    " " : {
      "comment" : "A placeholder text that appears when there is no inspiring verse available.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "- **Alif (ا)**: Functions as a long vowel 'aa' when used after a letter with a fatha. For example, كِتَاب (kitaab - book). Alif never carries tashkeel unless it represents Hamza." : {

    },
    "- **Waw (و)**: Functions as a long vowel 'uu' when used after a letter with a damma, like in رَسُول (rasool - messenger). As a consonant, it makes the 'w' sound, like in وَقَفَ (waqafa - stood)." : {

    },
    "- **Yaa (ي)**: Functions as a long vowel 'ii' when used after a letter with a kasra, like in كِتَابِي (kitaabi - my book). As a consonant, it makes the 'y' sound, like in يَد (yad - hand)." : {

    },
    "— %@" : {
      "comment" : "A footnote at the bottom of the \"Today's Practice\" card that includes the reference of the source text.",
      "isCommentAutoGenerated" : true
    },
    "“%@”" : {

    },
    "“All mankind is from Adam and Eve, an Arab has no superiority over a non-Arab nor a non-Arab has any superiority over an Arab; also a white has no superiority over a black, nor a black has any superiority over a white except by piety and good action.“" : {

    },
    "\"Taa marbuuTa\" means \"tied taa\" and is used to indicate the feminine gender in Arabic." : {

