    "Hamza on a Waw (ؤ): Appears after a damma or following a Waw." : {

    },
    "Hamza on a Yaa (ئ): Appears after a kasra or following a Yaa." : {

    },
    "Hamza on an Alif (أ or إ): When Hamza begins a word, it is written on an Alif. A fatha or damma places it above (أ), while a kasra places it below (إ)." : {

    },
    "Hamza on its own (ء): Used when Hamza appears in the middle or end of a word without a preceding vowel." : {

    },
    "Hamzatul waSl is always written as an Alif (ا) and is pronounced only if it begins a word at the start of speech. When the word follows another in a sentence, the hamzatul waSl is not pronounced, creating a smooth connection between words." : {

    },
    "Hamzatul waSl is usually not written with diacritics, but in learner texts or the Quran, it may be marked with a small ص above the Alif, indicating waSl." : {

    },
